  urldate = {2023-10-10},
  abstract = {Human aging is associated with an augmented pressor response to cold stress; however, whether this is due to alterations in sympathetic nervous system activation remains unclear. We hypothesized that whole-body cold stress elicits greater sympathetic nervous system responses in older (O) compared to young (Y) adults. Reflex vasoconstriction was induced in 7 Y (24{$\pm$}1 yr) and 6 O adults (66{$\pm$}2 yr) by lowering mean skin temperature (Tsk) from 34 to 30.5\textcelsius{} using a water-perfused suit. BP, muscle sympathetic nerve activity (MSNA; peroneal microneurography), and red blood cell flux (laser Doppler flowmetry; dorsum of foot) were measured continuously. Cutaneous vascular conductance (CVC=flux/mean BP) was expressed as a percent change from baseline. The increase in systolic BP during whole-body cold stress was greater in O adults ({$\increment$}2{$\pm$}1 Y v. {$\increment$}10{$\pm$}2 O mmHg; P{$<$}0.05); however, the increase in mean BP was not different ({$\increment$}5{$\pm$}1 Y v. {$\increment$}6{$\pm$}1 O mmHg; P{$>$}0.05). Reflex cutaneous vasoconstriction was attenuated in O adults (-31{$\pm$}6 Y v. -14{$\pm$}3 O \%{$\increment$}CVC; P{$<$}0.05). MSNA was greater in O adults at baseline (Tsk=34\textcelsius; 14{$\pm$}3 Y v. 25{$\pm$}2 O burst/min) and during cooling (Tsk=30.5\textcelsius; 14{$\pm$}4 Y v. 37{$\pm$}3 O burst/min; both P{$<$}0.05). MSNA increased during cooling in O, but not Y, adults ({$\increment$}-1{$\pm$}1 Y v. {$\increment$}12{$\pm$}3 O burst/min; P{$<$}0.05). These data suggest the MSNA response to cold stress is augmented, but peripheral vascular response is attenuated, in healthy aging. Grant Funding Source: Supported by HL120471-01 (JLG), AG007004-23 (WLK), HL093238-04 (LMA).},
