ance and quality of sleep after (r = 0.198), distance at 3.00\textendash 6.99 km/h and quality of sleep after training (r = 0.220), distance covered at {$>$}19.00 km/h and quality of sleep after training (r = 0.286), session duration and rested feeling after training (r = 0.227), total distance and rested feeling after training (r = 0.202), distance covered at 11.00\textendash 14.99 km/h and rested feeling after training (r = 0.222) and distance covered at {$>$}19.00 km/h and rested feeling after training (r = 0.214). In conclusion, sleep duration was longer in the training sessions during the middle of the week; the training intensity was also greater (485.8 {$\pm$} 56.8 A.U.). Moreover, sleep outcomes after training were slightly correlated with both physiological and locomotor demands.},
